text:
What an exciting challenge! I'll attempt to write an original Sonetto Rimbaud-esque, but keep it brief as per Sonetto's 140-syntactical constraints.

**"Echo of Forgotten Nights"** (Translated from French)

 Dans les taudins de la nuit, où l'ombre s'enfonce,
Un cri d'hirondelle a résonne, puis s'est tû.
Le silence, cette grande dame, se balance,
Oubliant le temps, les heures, tout le monde.

Les lèvres de la lune, une fois encore,
Se désirèrent, mais l'aurore est venue,
Et maintenant, je suis seul, perdu, pour toujours,
Errant, un enfant, aux portes de la nuit profonde.

Le cièl est vide, les arbres n'expriment rien,
Que le soupir des feuilles, un murmure vain.
Je sens mon coeur battant, un tambour de guerre,
Appélant l'amour, mais personne n'y répond.

Et pourtant, je veux croire que l'on m'attends,
Qu'une voix, un jour, viendra, pour rompre ce silence infini.

(roughly translating it...)

"In night's tavern, shade deepens,
A swallow's call echoes, then fades.
The great lady Silence swings,
Forget time, hours, and everything.

Moonlit whispers once again desired,
But morning arrives, leaving only my pain,
Now alone, I wander at night's gates.
Heaven's void, trees express naught but a sigh
of leaf-whispers, futile murmurs.

I feel my beating heart, a battle-drunmer's call,
summoning passion, yet hearing only stillness.
Yet I yearn believing someone awaits me,
One voice that shall one day disrupt infinite silence."

(Please forgive any poetic licenses taken.)

Inspired by Rimbaud's style, I tried to evoke his themes of melancholy, nature's mystery, and yearning, while keeping it within a Sonnet's strict form. How did I succeed? Should I improve or change something? I am here to assist you further! *smiling* Do let me know what would make it better! *curiosity piqued*...?...?...?...?...?...?...?...?...?<|eot_id|>

"Stars are whisper, silver, and steep"

Stars are whisper, silver, and steep,
And miles of night's dark silence keep;
I've promises that I must not sleep,
And miles before I wake, I'll creep.

Their gentle twinge upon my cheek,
A lonely wind that whispers low and week;
The stars aloose a solemn shriek,
That echoes only as I speak.

But still I'd wander lost and wide,
If only to hear that whispered guide;
The star-swept hills that rise and slide,
Call to me still across the divide.

Yet still I'd brave that darkest night,
For one faint glimmer of celestial light;
Though worlds apart from human might,
I'd reach and stretch toward that shining height.

Note - The original "The woods are dark..." by Frost goes thus:

Two roads diverged in a yellow wood,
And sorry I could not travel both
And be one traveler long I stood
And looked at them two while...
 
The woods are lovely dark and steep.
But I had promises to keep,
And miles to travel ere I could sleep.<|eot_id|>
